{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625565"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:26:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:26:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17035"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17035"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.06,0.03,0.67,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68762"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9725"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5113"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22877"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23056"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68762"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin D plays an essential role in calcium homeostasis and bone health. It undergoes several metabolic transformations in the body before becoming biologically active.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its metabolic activation pathway?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct activation in skin followed by intestinal absorption","Intestinal absorption followed by liver hydroxylation only","Intestinal absorption followed by kidney hydroxylation only","Skin synthesis followed by liver then kidney hydroxylation","Skin synthesis followed by kidney then liver hydroxylation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct pathway for vitamin D activation involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eskin synthesis followed by liver then kidney hydroxylation\u003C/strong\u003E. Ultraviolet B radiation converts 7-dehydrocholesterol in the skin to vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol). This undergoes 25-hydroxylation in the liver to form calcidiol, followed by 1\u03b1-hydroxylation in the kidneys to form calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D), the active hormone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect pathways can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect activation in skin followed by intestinal absorption\u003C/strong\u003E - The skin cannot produce the active form directly, as hydroxylation steps in both liver and kidneys are essential for activation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntestinal absorption followed by liver hydroxylation only\u003C/strong\u003E - While dietary sources contribute some vitamin D, the main source is skin synthesis, and kidney hydroxylation is also required for full activation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntestinal absorption followed by kidney hydroxylation only\u003C/strong\u003E - This pathway is incorrect as liver hydroxylation must occur before the kidney step can take place.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin synthesis followed by kidney then liver hydroxylation\u003C/strong\u003E - The sequence is incorrect, as liver hydroxylation must precede kidney hydroxylation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe active form of vitamin D increases calcium absorption in the intestine, promotes bone mineralisation, and helps maintain calcium homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is synthesised in the skin from 7-dehydrocholesterol upon exposure to ultraviolet B radiation.","Vitamin D3 must undergo hydroxylation in the liver to form 25-hydroxyvitamin D, then in the kidneys to form active 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D.","The active form of vitamin D increases calcium absorption in the intestine and promotes bone mineralisation."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Rebelos E, Tentolouris N, Jude E. The Role of Vitamin D in Health and Disease: A Narrative Review on the Mechanisms Linking Vitamin D with Disease and the Effects of Supplementation. Drugs. 2023;83(8):665-685. doi:10.1007/s40265-023-01875-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17035"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T15:34:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T15:35:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9725"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68762"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"